# Web Accessibility

- Preserve current visuals for typical users. Prefer semantic HTML, ARIA, `sr-only`, and `focus-visible` over visible layout changes.
- Ensure every interactive control has an accessible name. Icon-only buttons and links need `aria-label` or equivalent text.
- Keep keyboard navigation complete. Interactive elements must be reachable, operable with Enter/Space when appropriate, and show a visible `:focus-visible` state.
- Use real structure first: `button` for actions, `a`/`Link` for navigation, `nav`, `main`, `footer`, lists for grouped navigation, and headings in logical order.
- Label all form controls with visible text, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby`. Mark required fields and expose validation errors to assistive tech.
- Make dialogs, menus, tabs, comboboxes, sliders, and filter groups expose the expected ARIA roles, states, and labels when custom UI is used.
- Announce important dynamic updates with polite or assertive live regions instead of relying on visuals alone.
- Give images appropriate alt text: meaningful images need descriptive `alt`; decorative images should use empty `alt` or be hidden from assistive tech.
- Avoid redundant keyboard stops for duplicate navigation targets inside cards or composite widgets.

```tsx
// Good: no visual change, but accessible to screen readers and keyboard users.
<IconButton aria-label="Clear search">
  <XIcon aria-hidden="true" />
</IconButton>
```
